{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Kv26XqycxEMys5LtZ9BfGt","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Safety Guide\n     2→\n     3→This document covers good practices for using Cloche securely. The central concern is\n     4→the **Lethal Trifecta** of LLM-powered agent usage: when a system simultaneously has\n     5→(1) access to private data, (2) exposure to untrusted content, and (3) the ability to\n     6→communicate externally, it becomes vulnerable to prompt injection attacks that can\n     7→exfiltrate sensitive information. Cloche's architecture is designed to let you break this\n     8→trifecta, but only if you configure it correctly.\n     9→\n    10→## The Lethal Trifecta\n    11→\n    12→Any system that combines all three of the following is at risk:\n    13→\n    14→1. **Access to private data** — The agent can read source code, credentials, API keys,\n    15→   internal documentation, or customer data.\n    16→2. **Exposure to untrusted content** — The agent processes inputs that an attacker could\n    17→   influence: issue descriptions, pull request comments, dependency READMEs, web pages,\n    18→   or fetched API responses.\n    19→3. **Ability to communicate externally** — The agent can make HTTP requests, send emails,\n    20→   push to remote repositories, or otherwise transmit data outside the local environment.\n    21→\n    22→When all three are present, a prompt injection hidden in untrusted content can instruct\n    23→the agent to exfiltrate private data through the external communication channel. The\n    24→defense is to remove at least one leg of the trifecta.\n    25→\n    26→Cloche helps by isolating agent work inside containers where you control filesystem\n    27→access and network egress. But the host side of Cloche has no such isolation — host-side\n    28→agent steps run with the daemon's full OS privileges. The recommendations below focus on\n    29→keeping host-side exposure minimal and container-side access locked down.\n    30→\n    31→## Minimize Host-Side Agent Usage\n    32→\n    33→Host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`) run directly on the host machine. Agent steps in\n    34→host workflows inherit the daemon's permissions: full filesystem, full network, all\n    35→environment variables.\n    36→\n    37→**Prefer container workflows for agent work.** The `workflow` step type in `host.cloche`\n    38→dispatches work to an isolated container. Use it:\n    39→\n    40→```\n    41→workflow \"main\" {\n    42→  step prepare-prompt {\n    43→    run = \".cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    44→    results = [success, fail]\n    45→  }\n    46→\n    47→  step develop {\n    48→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    49→    results = [success, fail]\n    50→  }\n    51→\n    52→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n    53→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n    54→  develop:success        -> done\n    55→  develop:fail           -> abort\n    56→}\n    57→```\n    58→\n    59→In this pattern, the host workflow uses a *script* step (deterministic, no LLM) to\n    60→prepare the prompt and a *workflow* step to dispatch it to a container. No agent step\n    61→runs on the host.\n    62→\n    63→**If you must use host-side agent steps**, limit what the agent can access:\n    64→\n    65→- Run the daemon under a dedicated service account with restricted filesystem\n    66→  permissions rather than your personal user account.\n    67→- Avoid setting broad environment variables (cloud credentials, database URLs) in the\n    68→  daemon's environment. Only export what is strictly needed.\n    69→- Keep `host.cloche` simple — use it for orchestration (scripts and workflow dispatch),\n    70→  not for direct agent work.\n    71→\n    72→## Network Allowlisting\n    73→\n    74→Containers should have the minimum network access needed for their task. Cloche supports\n    75→a `network_allow` list in the `container {}` block that restricts egress to specific\n    76→domains:\n    77→\n    78→```\n    79→workflow \"develop\" {\n    80→  container {\n    81→    image         = \"my-project:latest\"\n    82→    network_allow = [\"api.anthropic.com\", \"github.com\"]\n    83→  }\n    84→\n    85→  step implement {\n    86→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    87→    results = [success, fail]\n    88→  }\n    89→\n    90→  implement:success -> done\n    91→  implement:fail    -> abort\n    92→}\n    93→```\n    94→\n    95→A good allowlist includes only:\n    96→\n    97→- The AI provider API endpoint (e.g. `api.anthropic.com`)\n    98→- Your git remote for pushing results (e.g. `github.com`)\n    99→- Language-specific package registries only if the workflow installs dependencies\n   100→\n   101→Everything else — documentation sites, third-party APIs, general internet — should be\n   102→excluded unless the task specifically requires it. The agent may be less capable without\n   103→web access, but the security tradeoff is worth it for tasks involving sensitive code.\n   104→\n   105→### Docker Network Isolation\n   106→\n   107→For additional control beyond `network_allow`, you can configure Docker-level network\n   108→restrictions in your project's Dockerfile or via `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS`:\n   109→\n   110→**Drop all network by default.** If your workflow does not need any network (e.g. pure\n   111→code editing with tests), override the container's network at the Docker level:\n   112→\n   113→```dockerfile\n   114→# In your .cloche/Dockerfile — no network-dependent steps\n   115→FROM cloche-base:latest\n   116→# Install all dependencies at build time so no runtime downloads needed\n   117→COPY requirements.txt .\n   118→RUN pip install -r requirements.txt\n   119→```\n   120→\n   121→When all dependencies are baked into the image, the container needs no outbound access\n   122→except for the AI provider API.\n   123→\n   124→**Restrict DNS resolution.** Containers use Docker's embedded DNS by default. For\n   125→tighter control, you can specify DNS servers that only resolve your allowlisted domains,\n   126→or use a DNS-based firewall.\n   127→\n   128→**Avoid `--privileged` and `--cap-add`.** Cloche containers do not need elevated\n   129→capabilities. The base image runs as an unprivileged `agent` user. Never run Cloche\n   130→containers with `--privileged` or add capabilities like `NET_ADMIN` unless you have a\n   131→specific, justified need.\n   132→\n   133→## Filesystem Isolation\n   134→\n   135→Cloche containers get a *copy* of your project, not a bind mount. This is a deliberate\n   136→security choice:\n   137→\n   138→- The agent cannot modify your host filesystem directly.\n   139→- Changes are only extracted back via `docker cp` to a git branch after the run\n   140→  completes.\n   141→- You review the changes in a branch before merging.\n   142→\n   143→**Keep this model intact.** Avoid using `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` to bind-mount sensitive\n   144→host directories into containers. If you need additional files in the container, prefer\n   145→the `.cloche/overrides/` mechanism, which copies files at container start time.\n   146→\n   147→**Audit override files.** Everything in `.cloche/overrides/` is applied on top of\n   148→`/workspace/` in the container. Do not place credentials or sensitive configuration in\n   149→this directory — it is checked into version control.\n   150→\n   151→## Credential Handling\n   152→\n   153→**API keys.** The `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` environment variable is automatically passed into\n   154→containers. Other environment variables must be explicitly passed via `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV`.\n   155→Only pass what the agent needs.\n   156→\n   157→**Git credentials.** Cloche copies `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` into containers for\n   158→agent authentication. These are copied (not mounted) so concurrent runs do not conflict.\n   159→Be aware that these files are present in the container filesystem during the run.\n   160→\n   161→**Do not bake secrets into Docker images.** Use environment variables or runtime\n   162→injection rather than embedding API keys, tokens, or passwords in your Dockerfile or\n   163→`.cloche/overrides/`.\n   164→\n   165→```\n   166→# Good: pass at runtime\n   167→CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV=DATABASE_URL=postgres://... cloche run develop\n   168→\n   169→# Bad: in Dockerfile\n   170→ENV DATABASE_URL=postgres://...\n   171→```\n   172→\n   173→## Prompt Hygiene\n   174→\n   175→The content of prompts is the primary vector for injection attacks. Untrusted content\n   176→that reaches an agent's prompt can instruct it to take unintended actions.\n   177→\n   178→**Separate trusted and untrusted content.** Prompt templates in `.cloche/prompts/` are\n   179→trusted — you write and review them. User requests (task descriptions, issue bodies) are\n   180→untrusted — they come from external sources. Cloche's prompt assembly concatenates these,\n   181→so the agent sees both. Keep the trusted template's instructions clear and explicit to\n   182→reduce the chance of injection overriding them.\n   183→\n   184→**Validate external inputs in script steps.** Use host-side script steps to sanitize or\n   185→filter task descriptions before passing them to agent steps. For example,\n   186→`.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` can strip HTML, limit length, or reject suspicious\n   187→patterns before writing to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   188→\n   189→**Limit feedback content.** The `feedback = \"true\"` step config includes previous output\n   190→logs in the prompt. If those logs contain content from untrusted sources (e.g. test\n   191→output that includes user-supplied data), this is another injection surface. Only enable\n   192→feedback when needed.\n   193→\n   194→## Review Before Merge\n   195→\n   196→Cloche extracts results to git branches, not directly to your main branch. Always review\n   197→the agent's changes before merging:\n   198→\n   199→- Check for unexpected file modifications outside the task scope.\n   200→- Look for new dependencies, network calls, or credential usage that the task did not\n   201→  require.\n   202→- Verify that no files were added that could serve as persistence mechanisms (cron jobs,\n   203→  git hooks, CI config changes).\n   204→\n   205→This review step is your final safeguard. Automated agents are powerful but not\n   206→infallible — treat their output with the same scrutiny you would give any external\n   207→contribution.\n   208→\n   209→## Summary\n   210→\n   211→| Risk | Mitigation |\n   212→|------|-----------|\n   213→| Host-side agent has full access | Use container workflows for agent steps; keep host workflows to scripts and dispatch |\n   214→| Unrestricted network in container | Use `network_allow` to limit egress to required domains |\n   215→| Sensitive files in container | Rely on copy-based isolation; avoid bind mounts; audit overrides |\n   216→| Credentials leaking | Pass via env vars at runtime, not in images or overrides |\n   217→| Prompt injection | Sanitize untrusted inputs in script steps; keep prompt templates explicit |\n   218→| Malicious agent output | Review branches before merging; check for unexpected changes |\n   219→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dbf10f22-a7e0-4657-b5f4-9a1bc4f6ad20","uuid":"664e5ee9-d00b-4b0d-9574-b7b0aa998940","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/SAFETY.md","content":"# Safety Guide\n\nThis document covers good practices for using Cloche securely. The central concern is\nthe **Lethal Trifecta** of LLM-powered agent usage: when a system simultaneously has\n(1) access to private data, (2) exposure to untrusted content, and (3) the ability to\ncommunicate externally, it becomes vulnerable to prompt injection attacks that can\nexfiltrate sensitive information. Cloche's architecture is designed to let you break this\ntrifecta, but only if you configure it correctly.\n\n## The Lethal Trifecta\n\nAny system that combines all three of the following is at risk:\n\n1. **Access to private data** — The agent can read source code, credentials, API keys,\n   internal documentation, or customer data.\n2. **Exposure to untrusted content** — The agent processes inputs that an attacker could\n   influence: issue descriptions, pull request comments, dependency READMEs, web pages,\n   or fetched API responses.\n3. **Ability to communicate externally** — The agent can make HTTP requests, send emails,\n   push to remote repositories, or otherwise transmit data outside the local environment.\n\nWhen all three are present, a prompt injection hidden in untrusted content can instruct\nthe agent to exfiltrate private data through the external communication channel. The\ndefense is to remove at least one leg of the trifecta.\n\nCloche helps by isolating agent work inside containers where you control filesystem\naccess and network egress. But the host side of Cloche has no such isolation — host-side\nagent steps run with the daemon's full OS privileges. The recommendations below focus on\nkeeping host-side exposure minimal and container-side access locked down.\n\n## Minimize Host-Side Agent Usage\n\nHost workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`) run directly on the host machine. Agent steps in\nhost workflows inherit the daemon's permissions: full filesystem, full network, all\nenvironment variables.\n\n**Prefer container workflows for agent work.** The `workflow` step type in `host.cloche`\ndispatches work to an isolated container. Use it:\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run = \".cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> abort\n}\n```\n\nIn this pattern, the host workflow uses a *script* step (deterministic, no LLM) to\nprepare the prompt and a *workflow* step to dispatch it to a container. No agent step\nruns on the host.\n\n**If you must use host-side agent steps**, limit what the agent can access:\n\n- Run the daemon under a dedicated service account with restricted filesystem\n  permissions rather than your personal user account.\n- Avoid setting broad environment variables (cloud credentials, database URLs) in the\n  daemon's environment. Only export what is strictly needed.\n- Keep `host.cloche` simple — use it for orchestration (scripts and workflow dispatch),\n  not for direct agent work.\n\n## Network Allowlisting\n\nContainers should have the minimum network access needed for their task. Cloche supports\na `network_allow` list in the `container {}` block that restricts egress to specific\ndomains:\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image         = \"my-project:latest\"\n    network_allow = [\"api.anthropic.com\", \"github.com\"]\n  }\n\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> done\n  implement:fail    -> abort\n}\n```\n\nA good allowlist includes only:\n\n- The AI provider API endpoint (e.g. `api.anthropic.com`)\n- Your git remote for pushing results (e.g. `github.com`)\n- Language-specific package registries only if the workflow installs dependencies\n\nEverything else — documentation sites, third-party APIs, general internet — should be\nexcluded unless the task specifically requires it. The agent may be less capable without\nweb access, but the security tradeoff is worth it for tasks involving sensitive code.\n\n### Docker Network Isolation\n\nFor additional control beyond `network_allow`, you can configure Docker-level network\nrestrictions in your project's Dockerfile or via `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS`:\n\n**Drop all network by default.** If your workflow does not need any network (e.g. pure\ncode editing with tests), override the container's network at the Docker level:\n\n```dockerfile\n# In your .cloche/Dockerfile — no network-dependent steps\nFROM cloche-base:latest\n# Install all dependencies at build time so no runtime downloads needed\nCOPY requirements.txt .\nRUN pip install -r requirements.txt\n```\n\nWhen all dependencies are baked into the image, the container needs no outbound access\nexcept for the AI provider API.\n\n**Restrict DNS resolution.** Containers use Docker's embedded DNS by default. For\ntighter control, you can specify DNS servers that only resolve your allowlisted domains,\nor use a DNS-based firewall.\n\n**Avoid `--privileged` and `--cap-add`.** Cloche containers do not need elevated\ncapabilities. The base image runs as an unprivileged `agent` user. Never run Cloche\ncontainers with `--privileged` or add capabilities like `NET_ADMIN` unless you have a\nspecific, justified need.\n\n## Filesystem Isolation\n\nCloche containers get a *copy* of your project, not a bind mount. This is a deliberate\nsecurity choice:\n\n- The agent cannot modify your host filesystem directly.\n- Changes are only extracted back via `docker cp` to a git branch after the run\n  completes.\n- You review the changes in a branch before merging.\n\n**Keep this model intact.** Avoid using `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` to bind-mount sensitive\nhost directories into containers. If you need additional files in the container, prefer\nthe `.cloche/overrides/` mechanism, which copies files at container start time.\n\n**Audit override files.** Everything in `.cloche/overrides/` is applied on top of\n`/workspace/` in the container. Do not place credentials or sensitive configuration in\nthis directory — it is checked into version control.\n\n## Credential Handling\n\n**API keys.** The `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` environment variable is automatically passed into\ncontainers. Other environment variables must be explicitly passed via `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV`.\nOnly pass what the agent needs.\n\n**Git credentials.** Cloche copies `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` into containers for\nagent authentication. These are copied (not mounted) so concurrent runs do not conflict.\nBe aware that these files are present in the container filesystem during the run.\n\n**Do not bake secrets into Docker images.** Use environment variables or runtime\ninjection rather than embedding API keys, tokens, or passwords in your Dockerfile or\n`.cloche/overrides/`.\n\n```\n# Good: pass at runtime\nCLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV=DATABASE_URL=postgres://... cloche run develop\n\n# Bad: in Dockerfile\nENV DATABASE_URL=postgres://...\n```\n\n## Prompt Hygiene\n\nThe content of prompts is the primary vector for injection attacks. Untrusted content\nthat reaches an agent's prompt can instruct it to take unintended actions.\n\n**Separate trusted and untrusted content.** Prompt templates in `.cloche/prompts/` are\ntrusted — you write and review them. User requests (task descriptions, issue bodies) are\nuntrusted — they come from external sources. Cloche's prompt assembly concatenates these,\nso the agent sees both. Keep the trusted template's instructions clear and explicit to\nreduce the chance of injection overriding them.\n\n**Validate external inputs in script steps.** Use host-side script steps to sanitize or\nfilter task descriptions before passing them to agent steps. For example,\n`.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` can strip HTML, limit length, or reject suspicious\npatterns before writing to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n\n**Limit feedback content.** The `feedback = \"true\"` step config includes previous output\nlogs in the prompt. If those logs contain content from untrusted sources (e.g. test\noutput that includes user-supplied data), this is another injection surface. Only enable\nfeedback when needed.\n\n## Review Before Merge\n\nCloche extracts results to git branches, not directly to your main branch. Always review\nthe agent's changes before merging:\n\n- Check for unexpected file modifications outside the task scope.\n- Look for new dependencies, network calls, or credential usage that the task did not\n  require.\n- Verify that no files were added that could serve as persistence mechanisms (cron jobs,\n  git hooks, CI config changes).\n\nThis review step is your final safeguard. Automated agents are powerful but not\ninfallible — treat their output with the same scrutiny you would give any external\ncontribution.\n\n## Summary\n\n| Risk | Mitigation |\n|------|-----------|\n| Host-side agent has full access | Use container workflows for agent steps; keep host workflows to scripts and dispatch |\n| Unrestricted network in container | Use `network_allow` to limit egress to required domains |\n| Sensitive files in container | Rely on copy-based isolation; avoid bind mounts; audit overrides |\n| Credentials leaking | Pass via env vars at runtime, not in images or overrides |\n| Prompt injection | Sanitize untrusted inputs in script steps; keep prompt templates explicit |\n| Malicious agent output | Review branches before merging; check for unexpected changes |\n","numLines":219,"startLine":1,"totalLines":219}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CDBvjAxrinnSypDty9oB2r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01DYUGkaDmeivE9DdDR2ug9Z","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Explore safety-relevant source code","subagent_type":"Explore","prompt":"Thoroughly explore the Cloche codebase to find all safety-relevant implementation details. I need to understand:\n\n1. **Container network configuration**: How Docker containers are configured, network allowlisting, what network settings are available. Look in internal/adapters/ for Docker-related code, and in any container configuration.\n\n2. **Host-side prompt handling**: How prompts are prepared and passed to containers. Look in internal/host/, .cloche/prompts/, .cloche/scripts/, and anywhere prompt templates are referenced.\n\n3. **Container isolation**: How the container model works — file copying, overlay handling, what gets mounted vs copied. Look in internal/adapters/docker/ or similar.\n\n4. **Workflow DSL security**: Any security-relevant aspects of the workflow DSL — step permissions, result handling, abort conditions.\n\n5. **Network allowlisting**: grep for \"allowlist\", \"network\", \"whitelist\", \"firewall\" in source code.\n\n6. **Agent adapter security**: How agent adapters work, what access they have, how they're sandboxed.\n\n7. **Any existing security documentation** in docs/.\n\nSearch broadly across the entire codebase. Look at Dockerfiles in .cloche/, configuration files, and all Go source code."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7777,"cache_read_input_tokens":8650,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7777},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dbf10f22-a7e0-4657-b5f4-9a1bc4f6ad20","uuid":"3032cd06-e328-4