{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MTq5Nyhd46v65XCLsjQCSo","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20→\n    21→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26→\n    27→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29→\n    30→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31→object with the following fields:\n    32→\n    33→| Field | Required | Description |\n    34→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40→\n    41→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44→reassignment.\n    45→\n    46→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47→file is a parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## Concepts\n    50→\n    51→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    58→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    59→\n    60→## Step Types\n    61→\n    62→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63→\n    64→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67→\n    68→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70→\n    71→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73→\n    74→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75→parse error.\n    76→\n    77→## DSL Syntax\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→workflow \"develop\" {\n    81→  container {\n    82→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    83→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    84→  }\n    85→\n    86→  step implement {\n    87→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88→    results = [success, fail]\n    89→  }\n    90→\n    91→  step test {\n    92→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    93→    results = [success, fail]\n    94→  }\n    95→\n    96→  step fix {\n    97→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    98→    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    99→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   100→  }\n   101→\n   102→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   103→  implement:success -> test\n   104→  implement:fail    -> abort\n   105→  test:success      -> done\n   106→  test:fail         -> fix\n   107→  fix:success       -> test\n   108→  fix:fail          -> abort\n   109→  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   110→}\n   111→```\n   112→\n   113→## Key Properties\n   114→\n   115→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   116→field makes it a script step.\n   117→\n   118→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   119→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   120→\n   121→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   122→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   123→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   124→\n   125→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   126→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   127→\n   128→## Wire Output Mappings\n   129→\n   130→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   131→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→The general form:\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   144→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   145→\n   146→| Expression | Meaning |\n   147→|---|---|\n   148→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   149→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   150→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01DYUGkaDmeivE9DdDR2ug9Z","session_id":"dbf10f22-a7e0-4657-b5f4-9a1bc4f6ad20","uuid":"637c55ce-7da0-4560-b819-d6d301feda20"}
